  finalize_turn (turn_finalizer.py)
     ├─ if budget exhausted: extra toolless call for summary
     ├─ persist session (SQLite)
     ├─ save_trajectory (optional JSONL)
     ├─ memory sync_all + queue prefetch
     └─ background memory/skill review trigger
     ↓
  return {final_response, messages, api_calls, completed, ...}

  3. Prompt Control: Three-Tier System Prompt

  agent/system_prompt.py builds the prompt once per session and caches it on agent._cached_system_prompt — critically, the system prompt is never re-rendered mid-session. This is the invariant that lets upstream
  KV/prompt caches stay warm (Anthropic's prefix cache, OpenRouter cache_control, llama.cpp KV reuse).

  Stable tier (cache-friendly, byte-stable for the session)

  - Identity (SOUL.md from HERMES_HOME or DEFAULT_AGENT_IDENTITY constant)
  - HERMES_AGENT_HELP_GUIDANCE (points to docs)
  - TASK_COMPLETION_GUIDANCE (universal "finish the job" rule)
  - Tool-aware guidance (MEMORY_GUIDANCE, SESSION_SEARCH_GUIDANCE, SKILLS_GUIDANCE, KANBAN_GUIDANCE, COMPUTER_USE_GUIDANCE) — gated on valid_tool_names
  - STEER_CHANNEL_NOTE — instructs model to trust the bounded out-of-band marker
  - Nous subscription block + tool-use enforcement (TOOL_USE_ENFORCEMENT_GUIDANCE) — model-family gated (gpt, codex, gemini, gemma, grok, glm, qwen, deepseek)
  - Model-family operational guidance (OPENAI_MODEL_EXECUTION_GUIDANCE for GPT/Codex/Grok, GOOGLE_MODEL_OPERATIONAL_GUIDANCE for Gemini)
  - Skills index (two-layer cache: in-process LRU + disk snapshot keyed by mtime/size manifest)
  - Environment hints (host OS, cwd, remote-backend probe for docker/modal/ssh, WSL, Termux)
  - Coding posture blocks (live git/workspace snapshot, frozen at session start)
  - Python environment probe (only when non-default)
  - Active profile hint
  - Platform hint (whatsapp, slack, discord, ...)

  Context tier (cwd-dependent)

  - Caller-supplied system_message
  - Context files discovered under TERMINAL_CWD: .cybernetics.md, CYBERNETICS.md, AGENTS.md, .cursorrules, CLAUDE.md — scanned for prompt injection via tools/threat_patterns.py before injection

  Volatile tier (rebuilt only on compression)

  - Memory snapshot (MEMORY.md)
  - USER.md profile
  - External memory provider block
  - Date-only timestamp (intentionally not minute-precision, to keep bytes stable across the day — issue #20451)

  Ephemeral injection (never reaches the cached prompt)

  - ephemeral_system_prompt is appended at API-call time only
  - Plugin context from pre_llm_call hooks is injected into the user message, not the system prompt
  - External-memory prefetch is fenced inside <memory-context> tags and injected into the user message (with a streaming scrubber to prevent leakage in the response)

  4. Context Window Management

  Preflight compression (turn_context.py:248-314)

  Before sending, rough token estimate (estimate_request_tokens_rough including tools schema) is compared to compressor.threshold_tokens (default max(context_length × 0.50, MINIMUM_CONTEXT_LENGTH)). Deferred when last
  real provider prompt_tokens fit under threshold.

  Compression algorithm (ContextCompressor.compress, context_compressor.py:2106)

  1. Pre-pass (cheap, no LLM call): _prune_old_tool_results replaces old tool results with 1-line summaries like [terminal] ran 'npm test' -> exit 0, 47 lines, dedupes identical reads, truncates large tool_call args.
  2. Protect head (protect_first_n=3, typically system + first user/assistant exchange).
  3. Find tail boundary by token budget (tail_token_budget = threshold × summary_target_ratio, ~20K tokens) — recent context.
  4. Summarize middle via auxiliary model with a structured template:
    - ## Active Task (the SINGLE most important field, verbatim quote of user's last unfulfilled input)
    - ## Goal, ## Constraints, ## Completed Actions (numbered with tool + outcome), ## Active State, ## Historical In-Progress, ## Blocked, ## Key Decisions, ## Resolved Questions, ## Historical Pending Asks, ## Relevant
   Files, ## Historical Remaining Work, ## Critical Context
    - Temporal anchoring directive: completed actions phrased as dated past-tense
    - Secrets explicitly redacted to [REDACTED]
  5. Iterative updates: stores _previous_summary so next compression updates rather than re-summarizing from scratch.
  6. Anti-thrashing: if last 2 compressions saved <10%, refuses to compress (asks user to /new or /compress <topic>).
  7. Failure modes: configurable — either abort (abort_on_summary_failure=True) or insert deterministic fallback summary listing tool calls + paths.
  8. Image stripping: replaces base64 image parts in compressed messages with placeholders.
  9. Role-alternation guard: summary inserted with role chosen to avoid consecutive same-role; merged into tail message if both choices collide.
  10. End marker: --- END OF CONTEXT SUMMARY — respond to the message below, not the summary above --- appended to prevent regurgitation (#11475, #14521, #33256).

  Special prefixes

  SUMMARY_PREFIX is a long carefully-worded preamble telling the model the summary is reference only, that the latest user message wins on any topic overlap, and that reverse signals ("stop", "undo") must terminate
  in-flight work. Multiple historical prefixes are tracked so legacy summaries can be re-normalized.

  5. Provider Adapters

  agent/transports/ defines a ProviderTransport ABC with four methods (convert_messages, convert_tools, build_kwargs, normalize_response). Registered transports:
  - anthropic_messages (Anthropic Messages API — adaptive thinking, signed thinking blocks, native cache_control)
  - codex_responses (OpenAI Responses API — call_id + response_item_id per tool call)
  - chat_completions (OpenAI-compatible — covers OpenRouter, vLLM, Ollama, llama.cpp, Mistral, Fireworks, Moonshot, GLM, DeepSeek, Kimi)
  - bedrock

  All responses normalize to NormalizedResponse(content, tool_calls, finish_reason, reasoning, usage, provider_data). Protocol-specific state (Codex call_id, Gemini thought_signature, Anthropic reasoning_details +
  interleaved content blocks) lives in provider_data dicts and is accessed via @property shims for back-compat with the 45+ sites that read tc.function.name.

  The AIAgent retains client construction, streaming, credential refresh, prompt caching, interrupt handling, and retry logic.

  6. Tool Execution Pipeline

  execute_tool_calls_concurrent (tool_executor.py:243):
  1. Interrupt check — cancel all if requested.
  2. Parse args + unwrap tool_call bridge (Tool Search dispatches the underlying tool directly with session-scope enforcement at this layer).
  3. Request middleware + plugin pre-tool-call block + ToolGuardrails.before_call decision.
  4. Checkpoint preflight (snapshot before write_file/patch or destructive terminal commands).
  5. Concurrent dispatch via thread pool; each worker registers its TID so interrupt() can fan out, propagates ContextVars (#13617 GHSA fix), and sets thread-local activity callback for heartbeats.
  6. Result classification: file-mutation verifier records success/failure; _apply_pending_steer_to_tool_results appends /steer text to the last tool message.

  ToolGuardrails (tool_guardrails.py) is pure (no side effects) and tracks: exact-failure repeats, same-tool-failure repeats, no-progress on idempotent tools. Defaults are warning-only; circuit-breaker is opt-in.

  7. Resilience Features

  - Iteration budget (IterationBudget) with one grace call after exhaustion
  - Sanitization passes: surrogates, non-ASCII, _repair_tool_call_arguments, _repair_message_sequence (role alternation)
  - Empty-content retry with thinking-prefill recovery
  - Length-finish continuation prompts distinguishing partial-stream-stub from natural truncation
  - Fallback provider chain activates eagerly on 429/billing errors (with pool-rotation exception)
  - Rate-limit cross-session guard for Nous Portal (file-based)
  - Stale-connection cleanup + keepalive HTTP client
  - Per-thread interrupt with explicit signal pending state
  - Checkpoint manager for snapshots before destructive operations
  - Prompt-injection blocks in context files via shared threat_patterns.py

  ---
  Pros

  1. Cache-Conscious Prompt Design

  The three-tier (stable/context/volatile) split with date-only timestamps, normalized whitespace, and sorted tool_call JSON keys is unusually disciplined. Anthropic's prefix cache + OpenRouter cache_control +
  local-server KV reuse all benefit. This is a measurable cost reduction (~75% input-token savings claimed on multi-turn).

  2. Defense in Depth Against Prompt Injection

  Four distinct mitigations: (a) context-file scanner using shared threat_patterns.py, (b) bounded [OUT-OF-BAND USER MESSAGE] marker with STEER_CHANNEL_NOTE telling the model to trust ONLY this exact marker, (c)
  <memory-context> fence tags + streaming scrubber to prevent leakage, (d) secret redaction in summary outputs (LLM may ignore prompt instructions and echo secrets).

  3. Sophisticated Compression

  The structured summary template (Active Task as primary field, Historical/Pending sections framed as "stale", explicit reverse-signal handling, end markers, iterative updates) shows production scarring from many
  specific failure modes (issues cited inline: #11475, #14521, #33256, #38788, #40803, #41607). Anti-thrashing + cooldown + deterministic fallback prevent runaway loops.

  4. Provider Portability via Clean Abstraction

  ProviderTransport ABC with NormalizedResponse + provider_data dict pattern is well-designed: the shared surface stays minimal, protocol-specific state has a clear home, and back-compat shims preserve the 45+ existing
  call sites.

  5. Granular Failure Recovery

  Distinct retry counters for invalid tool names, invalid JSON args, empty content, incomplete scratchpad, thinking prefill, codex incomplete — each with bounded retries and tailored recovery (synthetic tool results vs
  continuation prompts vs prefill). Far more graceful than monolithic exception handling.

  6. Hot-Path Observability

  Plugin hooks (pre_llm_call, pre_api_request, pre_tool_call_block, on_session_start, etc.), step callbacks for gateway streaming, activity touches for heartbeats — all wired without polluting the core loop too badly.
  Langfuse plugin is a real customer.

  7. Multi-Surface Support

  One agent runs CLI, TUI, gateway daemon, kanban worker, MCP server, ACP adapter, desktop GUI, web. The plumbing (TERMINAL_CWD, platform key, session_id, parent_session_id) was clearly designed for this from day one.

  8. Security-Aware Tool Execution

  Checkpoints before destructive operations; per-thread interrupt fan-out; ContextVar propagation (#13617 fixed a real concurrency vulnerability); webhook-safe toolset constraint; cross-profile write guard; sandbox-aware
   environment hints.

  ---
  Cons

  1. Severe Monolithic Files Despite Decomposition

  run_agent.py is still 239KB / ~5,400 LOC with a single AIAgent class and 200+ methods. conversation_loop.py:run_conversation is ~5,400 lines (file is 241KB). context_compressor.py is 113KB. cli.py is 637KB (13,933 LOC)
   — extreme. Reading order is dictated by knowing the symbol name; cognitive load to onboard is very high.

  2. Mutating-agent-as-State-Container Pattern

  build_turn_context mutates agent._invalid_tool_retries, agent._invalid_json_retries, agent._empty_content_retries, agent._incomplete_scratchpad_retries, ..., agent.iteration_budget, agent._cached_system_prompt,
  agent._execution_thread_id, etc. — 30+ side effects per turn. Tests that don't reset all of them silently leak state. The "extracted to module but still mutates agent" refactor pattern is everywhere.

  3. Heavy Use of _ra() Indirection for Test Patchability

  agent/conversation_loop.py:118 _ra() and agent/system_prompt.py:66 _ra() exist so that mock.patch("run_agent.X") keeps working after extraction. This is honest pragmatism, but it creates a "patch contract" that future
  refactors can't see — touching run_agent's namespace is now an API change.

  4. Provider-Specific Special Cases Bleed Everywhere

  The conversation loop has explicit branches for: Anthropic long-context tier reduction, Nous Portal rate-limit cross-session guard, GitHub Models 8K cap, Azure content filter language, OpenRouter cache headers, Alibaba
   glm-4.7 model-name workaround, Moonshot reasoning_content field, Kimi/DeepSeek/MiMo "require-side" reasoning replay, Mistral strict-field stripping. The ProviderTransport abstraction doesn't fully contain provider
  quirks — the loop knows about all of them.

  5. System Prompt is Caller-Implicit

  The prompt is built from agent.valid_tool_names, agent.platform, agent.model, agent.provider, os.environ["TERMINAL_CWD"], os.environ["HERMES_KANBAN_TASK"], os.environ["HERMES_PLATFORM"], os.environ["HERMES_DESKTOP"],
  os.environ["HERMES_DESKTOP_TERMINAL"], os.environ["HERMES_ENVIRONMENT_HINT"], config.yaml entries... A dev cannot easily predict what the model will see without running it. There's no dump_prompt --explain
  introspection (or it's not surfaced).

  6. Compression is High-Stakes But Best-Effort

  Single auxiliary-model failure means the entire middle window can be replaced with a deterministic "summary unavailable" placeholder that loses most context. The fallback summary lists tool calls + paths but not
  decisions or content. Some configurations abort entirely, freezing the session. Either outcome is bad UX if the auxiliary provider is flaky.

  7. Stable Tier Can Be Very Heavy

  For a default coding session with skills enabled: SOUL.md + ~6 guidance blocks + skills index (potentially hundreds of skills with descriptions) + environment hints + coding context blocks + profile hint = often 8-15K
  tokens before any conversation starts. Combined with tool schemas (~3-5K tokens for the full Cybernetics tool set), the floor is large. The GitHub Models 8K cap message admits this directly.

  8. Tight Coupling Between "Layers"

  agent/conversation_loop.py imports from agent.codex_responses_adapter, agent.bedrock_adapter, agent.anthropic_adapter, agent.transports.*, plus tools.*, hermes_cli.*, gateway.*, plugins.*. There's no clean stack — each
   "extracted" module re-couples back. The god-file decomposition plan in the repo is honest about being a work in progress.

  9. Streaming + Tool Calls + Reasoning is Brittle

  Special handling for: think-block scrubber, memory-context scrubber, thinking-only assistant turns dropped before API send, signed thinking block replay for Anthropic, Gemini thought_signature replay, Codex reasoning
  items round-trip. Each provider's reasoning surface is bespoke. Several issues cited inline acknowledge silent failure modes here.

  10. Memory Provider Restriction is a Footgun

  Only ONE external memory provider allowed at a time (memory_manager.py:8). The single-provider rule is defensible (tool schema bloat, conflicting backends) but the rejection-with-warning means second registration
  silently no-ops — easy to miss.

  11. Date-Only Timestamp Trades Off Recency

  The cache stability win (date-only) means the model has no minute-precision clock from the prompt. The mitigation ("query the exact wall-clock time via tools when it actually needs it") relies on the model remembering
  to do so. Some models will hallucinate the time.

  12. Compression Summary as "user" or "assistant" Role

  Inserting the summary as either role has known regression modes (#11475 user-role, #33256 assistant-role) that required adding the end marker as a workaround. The merge-into-tail fallback is even more fragile — it
  prepends a multi-thousand-token blob to whatever the next message contains. Models occasionally read this as if the user wrote the summary.

  ---
  Bottom Line

  The architecture is production-hardened with visible scar tissue from many real incidents — the codebase is unusually honest about its failure modes (issue numbers, "burned by", "wedged" comments throughout). The
  prompt/context control is sophisticated: caching is taken seriously, prompt-injection defense has multiple layers, compression has a thoughtful structured template, and provider portability is well-abstracted at the
  transport seam.

  The major structural cost is monolithic god-files and pervasive mutation of agent-as-state-container, which makes the system hard to reason about top-down. Extracted modules still pull state from agent and patch back
  through _ra() for tests — the "refactor" has flattened the call graph without genuinely decoupling.

  If you're evaluating this for adoption: the agent loop, prompt assembly, and compression strategy are worth studying as reference designs. The provider transport abstraction is clean. The internal coupling and file
  sizes are the price of a feature surface this large; budget significant onboarding time.

